Cold starts and concurrency.

A cold start is the extra latency you pay when Lambda has to download your code, start the runtime, and run the init code before the handler can run. It happens on the very first invocation, after an idle period, or when Lambda scales out to handle more concurrency. A warm start skips all of that and goes straight to the handler. Cold-start cost depends mostly on the runtime: Python and Node take about one hundred to two hundred milliseconds, while Java and dot-NET take five hundred milliseconds to over a second because of J-V-M or C-L-R startup, and container images vary. You reduce the pain by keeping the deployment package small, moving heavy setup into init code so it runs once per environment, choosing a lighter runtime, and, for latency-sensitive surfaces, using Provisioned Concurrency, which keeps a number of environments permanently warm. You pay for that capacity even when idle.

Concurrency is the number of execution environments running your function at the same time. The account has a regional pool, defaulting to one thousand, shared by every function without a reservation. Reserved concurrency pins a slice to a specific function. It both guarantees that the function always has at least that capacity, so nothing else can starve it, and caps the function at that limit. The classic use is protecting a downstream resource: if a database handles fifty connections, cap the Lambda at fifty. Provisioned concurrency is orthogonal; it pre-warms environments to eliminate cold starts.

When a function exceeds its concurrency limit, Lambda throttles. Synchronous callers get an H-T-T-P four-twenty-nine immediately. Asynchronous events are queued and retried. And event source mappings simply back off.
